//
//  A caveat worth learning now: this is NEGATION AS FAILURE, and it is
//  GROUND-ONLY — it means "no answer given what's currently known", so you must
//  GENERATE first and negate on known values. (For constrain-then-generate you
//  reach for \`dif\` from the last exercise instead. The Book's Lesson 2 walks
//  through the failure mode on purpose.)
//
//  WORKED EXAMPLE — 2 is in the list, so its "absent" check fails and we fall
//  through to "present":
//
//      one { (all { member(2, xs) } = []; "absent") | "present" }  → "present"
//
//  YOUR TURN: check whether 9 is absent from the list. The \`all { … } = []\`
